When math\_clz32 is called with one argument `x`, the following steps are taken:
Let n be ToUint32(x).
Let p be the number of leading zero bits in the 32-bit binary representation of n.
Return p.

NOTE:
  
If n is 0, p will be 32. If the most significant bit of the 32-bit binary encoding of n is 1,
p will be 0.

the natural logarithms). The result is computed in a way that is accurate even
when the value of `x` is close to 0.

label: math_floor
title: math_floor(x) → {number}
description:

computes the greatest (closest to +∞) Number value that is not greater than `x`
and is an integer.
  
If `x` is already an integer, the result is `x`.

NOTE:
The value of math\_floor(x) is the same as the value of -math\_ceil(-x).

label: math_fround
title: math_fround(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_fround(x) → {number}

When math\_fround is called with argument `x`, the following steps are taken:

1. If `x` is NaN, return NaN.
2. If `x` is one of +0, -0, +∞, -∞, return `x`.
3. Let x32 be the result of converting `x` to a value in IEEE 754-2008 binary32 format using roundTiesToEven mode.
4. Let x64 be the result of converting x32 to a value in IEEE 754-2008 binary64 format.
5. Return the ECMAScript Number value corresponding to x64.

label: math_hypot

computes the square root
of the sum of squares of its arguments.
  
If no arguments are passed, the result is +0.

label: math_imul
title: math_imul(x, x) → {number}

#### math\_imul(x, x) → {number}

When math\_imul is called with arguments `x` and `y`,
the following steps are taken:

1. Let a be ToUint32(x).
2. Let b be ToUint32(y).
3. Let product be (a × b) modulo 232.
4. If product ≥ 231, return product - 232; otherwise return product.

label: accumulate
title: accumulate(f, initial, xs) → {value}
description:
#### accumulate(f, initial, xs) → {value}

Applies binary
function `f` to the elements of `xs` from
right-to-left order, first applying `f` to the last element
and the value `initial`, resulting in `r`1,
then to the
second-last element and `r`1, resulting in
`r`2,
etc, and finally
to the first element and `r`n-1, where
`n` is the length of the
list. Thus, `accumulate(f,zero,list(1,2,3))` results in
`f(1, f(2, f(3, zero)))`.
Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`), space: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`),
where `n` is the length of `xs`.

label: equal
title: equal(x, y) → {boolean}
description:
#### equal(x, y) → {boolean}

Returns `true` if both
have the same structure with respect to `pair`,
and identical values at corresponding leave positions (places that are not
themselves pairs), and `false` otherwise. For the "identical",
the values need to have the same type, otherwise the result is
`false`. If corresponding leaves are boolean values, these values
need to be the same. If both are `undefined` or both are
`null`, the result is `true`. Otherwise they are compared
with `===` (using the definition of `===` in the
respective Source language in use).
Time, space:
`Theta(n)`, where `n` is the total number of data structures such as
pairs in `x` and `y`.

`f` is applied element-by-element:

`fun(1)` and `fun(2)`.

label: list_to_string
title: list_to_string(xs) → {string}
description:
#### list\_to\_string(xs) → {string}

Returns a string that represents
list `xs` using the text-based box-and-pointer notation
`[...]`.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)` where `n` is the size of the list, space: `Theta(m)` where `m` is the length of the string.
The process is iterative, but consumes space `O(m)`
because of the result string.

label: map
title: map(f, xs) → {list}
description:
#### map(f, xs) → {list}

Returns a list that results from list
`xs` by element-wise application of unary function `f`.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`),
space: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`), where `n` is the length of `xs`.
`f` is applied element-by-element:
`map(f, list(1, 2))` results in `list(f(1), f(2))`.

label: math_abs
title: math_abs(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_abs(x) → {number}

computes the absolute value of x; the result has the same magnitude as `x` but has positive sign.

label: math_acos
title: math_acos(x) → {number}

label: math_acosh
title: math_acosh(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_acosh(x) → {number}

computes the inverse hyperbolic cosine of `x`.

label: math_asin
title: math_asin(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_asin(x) → {number}

computes the arc sine of `x`. The result is expressed in radians and ranges from -π / 2 to +π / 2.

label: math_asinh
title: math_asinh(x) → {number}

label: math_atan
title: math_atan(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_atan(x) → {number}

computes the arc tangent of `x`. The result is expressed in radians and ranges from -π / 2 to +π / 2.

label: math_atan2
title: math_atan2(y, x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_atan2(y, x) → {number}

computes the arc tangent of the quotient `y` / `x` of the arguments `y` and `x`, where the signs of `y` and `x` are used to determine the quadrant of the result. Note that it is intentional and traditional for the two-argument arc tangent function that the argument named `y` be first and the argument named `x` be second. The result is expressed in radians and ranges from -π to +π.

label: math_atanh
title: math_atanh(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_atanh(x) → {number}

computes the inverse hyperbolic tangent of `x`.

label: math_cbrt
title: math_cbrt(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_cbrt(x) → {number}

computes the cube root of `x`.

label: math_ceil
title: math_ceil(x) → {number}

label: math_clz32
title: math_clz32(n) → {number}
description:
#### math\_clz32(n) → {number}

When math\_clz32 is called with one argument `x`, the following steps are taken:
Let n be ToUint32(x).
Let p be the number of leading zero bits in the 32-bit binary representation of n.
Return p.

NOTE:
  
If n is 0, p will be 32. If the most significant bit of the 32-bit binary encoding of n is 1,
p will be 0.

label: math_cos
title: math_cos(x) → {number}

label: math_cosh
title: math_cosh(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_cosh(x) → {number}

computes the hyperbolic cosine of `x`.

NOTE:
The value of cosh(x) is the same as (exp(x) + exp(-x)) / 2.

label: math_exp
title: math_exp(x) → {number}

label: math_expm1
title: math_expm1(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_expm1(x) → {number}

computes subtracting 1 from the
exponential function of `x` (e raised to the power of `x`, where e is the base of
the natural logarithms). The result is computed in a way that is accurate even
when the value of `x` is close to 0.

label: math_floor
title: math_floor(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_floor(x) → {number}

computes the greatest (closest to +∞) Number value that is not greater than `x`
and is an integer.
  
If `x` is already an integer, the result is `x`.

NOTE:
The value of math\_floor(x) is the same as the value of -math\_ceil(-x).

label: math_fround
title: math_fround(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_fround(x) → {number}

When math\_fround is called with argument `x`, the following steps are taken:

1. If `x` is NaN, return NaN.
2. If `x` is one of +0, -0, +∞, -∞, return `x`.
3. Let x32 be the result of converting `x` to a value in IEEE 754-2008 binary32 format using roundTiesToEven mode.
4. Let x64 be the result of converting x32 to a value in IEEE 754-2008 binary64 format.
5. Return the ECMAScript Number value corresponding to x64.

label: math_hypot
title: math_hypot() → {number}
description:
#### math\_hypot() → {number}

computes the square root
of the sum of squares of its arguments.
  
If no arguments are passed, the result is +0.

label: math_imul
title: math_imul(x, x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_imul(x, x) → {number}

When math\_imul is called with arguments `x` and `y`,
the following steps are taken:

1. Let a be ToUint32(x).
2. Let b be ToUint32(y).
3. Let product be (a × b) modulo 232.
4. If product ≥ 231, return product - 232; otherwise return product.

label: math_log
title: math_log(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_log(x) → {number}

Computes the natural logarithm of `x`.

label: math_log1p
title: math_log1p(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_log1p(x) → {number}

computes the natural logarithm of 1 + `x`. The result is computed in a way that is accurate even when the value of `x` is close to zero.

label: math_log2
title: math_log2(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_log2(x) → {number}

computes the base 2 logarithm of `x`.

label: math_log10
title: math_log10(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_log10(x) → {number}

computes the base 10 logarithm of `x`.

label: math_max
title: math_max() → {number}
description:
#### math\_max() → {number}

Given zero or more numbers, returns the largest of them.
  
If no arguments are given, the result is -∞.
  
If any value is NaN, the result is NaN.
The comparison of values to determine the largest value is done using the
Abstract Relational Comparison algorithm except that +0 is considered to be larger than -0.

label: math_min
title: math_min() → {number}
description:
#### math\_min() → {number}

Given zero or more arguments, returns the smallest of them.
  
If no arguments are given, the result is +∞.
  
If any value is NaN, the result is NaN.
The comparison of values to determine the smallest value is done using the
Abstract Relational Comparison algorithm except that +0 is considered to be larger than -0.

label: math_pow
title: math_pow(base, exponent) → {number}

label: math_random
title: math_random() → {number}
description:
#### math\_random() → {number}

Returns a number value with positive sign, greater than or equal to 0 but less than 1,
chosen randomly or pseudo randomly with approximately uniform distribution over that
range, using an implementation-dependent algorithm or strategy. This function takes no arguments.
Each math\_random function created for distinct realms must produce a distinct sequence
of values from successive calls.

label: math_round
title: math_round(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_round(x) → {number}

Returns the number value that is closest to `x` and is an integer.
  
If two integers are equally close to `x`, then the result is the Number value
that is closer to +∞. If `x` is already an integer, the result is `x`.
NOTE 1:
math\_round(3.5) returns 4, but math\_round(-3.5) returns -3.

label: math_sign
title: math_sign(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_sign(x) → {number}

Computes the sign of `x`, indicating whether `x` is positive, negative, or zero.

label: math_sin
title: math_sin(x) → {number}

label: math_sinh
title: math_sinh(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_sinh(x) → {number}

Computes the hyperbolic sine of `x`.

NOTE:
The value of sinh(x) is the same as (exp(x) - exp(-x)) / 2.

label: math_sqrt
title: math_sqrt(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_sqrt(x) → {number}

Computes the square root of `x`.

label: math_tan
title: math_tan(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_tan(x) → {number}

Computes the tangent of `x`. The argument is expressed in radians.

label: math_tanh
title: math_tanh(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_tanh(x) → {number}

Computes the hyperbolic tangent of `x`.

NOTE:
The value of `math_tanh(x)` is the same as
`(exp(x) - exp(-x))/(exp(x) + exp(-x))`.

label: math_trunc
title: math_trunc(x) → {number}

label: member
title: member(v, xs) → {list}
description:
#### member(v, xs) → {list}

Returns first postfix sublist
whose head is identical to
`v` (using `===`); returns `null` if the
element does not occur in the list.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)`,
space: `Theta(1)`, where `n` is the length of `xs`.

label: pair
title: pair(x, y) → {pair}

label: parse_int
title: parse_int(s, i) → {number}
description:
#### parse\_int(s, i) → {number}

Interprets a given string `s` as an integer,
using the positive integer `i` as radix,
and returns the respective value.
  
Examples: `parse_int("909", 10)` returns the number
`909`, and `parse_int("-1111", 2)` returns the number
`-15`.  

See [ECMAScript Specification, Section 18.2.5](https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/9.0/index.html#sec-parseint-string-radix) for details.

label: prompt
title: prompt(s) → {string}
description:
#### prompt(s) → {string}

Pops up a window that displays the string `s`, provides
an input line for the user to enter a text, a `Cancel` button and an `OK` button.
The call of `prompt`
suspends execution of the program until one of the two buttons is pressed. If
the `OK` button is pressed, `prompt` returns the entered text as a string.
If the `Cancel` button is pressed, `prompt` returns a non-string value.

label: remove
title: remove(v, xs) → {list}
description:
#### remove(v, xs) → {list}

Returns a list that results from
`xs` by removing the first item from `xs` that
is identical (`===`) to `v`.
Returns the original
list if there is no occurrence. Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)`, space: `Theta(n)`, where `n`
is the length of `xs`.

label: remove_all
title: remove_all(v, xs) → {list}
description:
#### remove\_all(v, xs) → {list}

Returns a list that results from
`xs` by removing all items from `xs` that
are identical (`===`) to `v`.
Returns the original
list if there is no occurrence.
Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)`, space: `Theta(n)`, where `n`
is the length of `xs`.

label: reverse
title: reverse(xs) → {list}
description:
#### reverse(xs) → {list}

Returns list `xs` in reverse
order. Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)`,
space: `Theta(n)`, where `n` is the length of `xs`.
The process is iterative, but consumes space `Theta(n)`
because of the result list.

label: stringify
title: stringify(v) → {string}
description:
#### stringify(v) → {string}

returns a string that represents the value `v`, using a
notation that is is consistent with
[JSON](http://www.ecma-international.org/publications/files/ECMA-ST/ECMA-404.pdf),
but also displays `undefined`, `NaN`, `Infinity`, and function objects.
See also [textbook example](https://sourceacademy.org/sicpjs/3.3.5).

label: tail
title: tail(p) → {value}
description:
#### tail(p) → {value}

\*\*primitive\*\*; returns tail (second component of given pair `p`; time: `Theta(1)Theta(1)`.

label: Infinity
title: Infinity:number
description:
#### Infinity:number

The name `Infinity` refers to the special number value `Infinity`.
See [ECMAScript Specification, Section 4.3.23](https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/9.0/index.html#sec-value-properties-of-the-global-object-infinity)

label: math_E
title: math_E:number
description:
#### math\_E:number

The Number value for e, Euler's number,
which is approximately 2.718281828459045.

label: math_LN2
title: math_LN2:number
description:
#### math\_LN2:number

The Number value for the natural logarithm of 2,
which is approximately 0.6931471805599453.

label: math_LN10
title: math_LN10:number
description:
#### math\_LN10:number

The Number value for the natural logarithm of 10,
which is approximately 2.302585092994046.

label: math_LOG2E
title: math_LOG2E:number
description:
#### math\_LOG2E:number

The Number value for the base-2 logarithm of eℝ, the base of the natural logarithms;
this value is approximately 1.4426950408889634.

NOTE:
The value of math\_LOG2E is approximately the reciprocal of the value of math\_LN2.

label: math_LOG10E
title: math_LOG10E:number
description:
#### math\_LOG10E:number

The Number value for the base-10 logarithm of e,
the base of the natural logarithms; this value is approximately 0.4342944819032518.

NOTE:
The value of math\_LOG10E is approximately the reciprocal of the value of math\_LN10.

label: math_PI
title: math_PI:number
description:
#### math\_PI:number

The Number value for π, the ratio of the circumference of a circle to its diameter,
which is approximately 3.1415926535897932.

label: math_SQRT1_2
title: math_SQRT1_2:number
description:
#### math\_SQRT1\_2:number

The Number value for the square root of 0.5, which is approximately 0.7071067811865476.

NOTE:
The value of math\_SQRT1\_2 is approximately the reciprocal of the value of math\_SQRT2.

label: math_SQRT2
title: math_SQRT2:number
description:
#### math\_SQRT2:number

The Number value for the square root of 2, which is approximately 1.4142135623730951.

label: NaN
title: NaN:number
description:
#### NaN:number

The name `NaN` refers to the special number value `NaN` ("not a number"). Note that
`NaN` is a number, as specified by `is_number`.
See [ECMAScript Specification, Section 4.3.24](https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/9.0/index.html#sec-value-properties-of-the-global-object-nan)

label: undefined
title: undefined:undefined
description:
#### undefined:undefined

The name `undefined` refers to the special value `undefined`.
See also [textbook explanation in section 4.1.1](https://sourceacademy.org/sicpjs/4.1.1#h5).

label: __access_export__
title: __access_export__(exports, lookup_name) → {value}
description:
#### \_\_access\_export\_\_(exports, lookup\_name) → {value}

Searches for the specified name in the data structure of exported names.
The data structure is a pair where the head element is the default export
and the tail element is a list of pairs where each pair is a mapping from
the exported name to the value being exported. If the lookup name is
"default", the default export is returned instead of a named export. If
the name does not exist, `undefined` is returned.

label: __access_named_export__
title: __access_named_export__(named_exports, lookup_name) → {value}
description:
#### \_\_access\_named\_export\_\_(named\_exports, lookup\_name) → {value}

Searches for the specified name in the data structure of exported names.
The data structure is a list of pairs where each pair is a mapping from
the exported name to the value being exported. If the name does not exist,
`undefined` is returned.

label: accumulate
title: accumulate(f, initial, xs) → {value}
description:
#### accumulate(f, initial, xs) → {value}

Applies binary
function `f` to the elements of `xs` from
right-to-left order, first applying `f` to the last element
and the value `initial`, resulting in `r`1,
then to the
second-last element and `r`1, resulting in
`r`2,
etc, and finally
to the first element and `r`n-1, where
`n` is the length of the
list. Thus, `accumulate(f,zero,list(1,2,3))` results in
`f(1, f(2, f(3, zero)))`.
Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`), space: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`),
where `n` is the length of `xs`.

label: append
title: append(xs, ys) → {list}
description:
#### append(xs, ys) → {list}

Returns a list that results from
appending the list `ys` to the list `xs`.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)`, space:
`Theta(n)`, where `n` is the length of `xs`.
In the result, null at the end of the first argument list
is replaced by the second argument, regardless what the second
argument consists of.

label: arity
title: arity(f) → {number}

label: array_length
title: array_length(x) → {number}
description:
#### array\_length(x) → {number}

\*\*primitive\*\*; returns
the current length of array `x`, which is 1 plus the
highest index that has been used so far in an array assignment on
`x`. Here literal array expressions are counted too: The
array `[10, 20, 30]` has a length of 3.
Time: `Θ(1)`, space: `Θ(1)`

label: build_list
title: build_list(f, n) → {list}
description:
#### build\_list(f, n) → {list}

Makes a list with `n`
elements by applying the unary function `f`
to the numbers 0 to `n - 1`, assumed to be a nonnegative integer.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`), space: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`).

label: build_stream
title: build_stream(f, n) → {stream}
description:
#### build\_stream(f, n) → {stream}

Makes a stream with `n`
elements by applying the unary function `f`
to the numbers 0 to `n - 1`, assumed to be a nonnegative integer.
Lazy? Yes: The result stream forces the application of `f`
for the next element

label: char_at
title: char_at(s, i) → {string}
description:
#### char\_at(s, i) → {string}

Takes a string `s` as first argument and a nonnegative integer
`i` as second argument. If `i` is less than the length
of `s`, this function returns a one-character string that contains
the character of `s` at position `i`, counting from 0.
If `i` is larger than or equal to the length of
`s`, this function returns `undefined`.

label: display
title: display(v, s) → {value}
description:
#### display(v, s) → {value}

Optional second argument. If present,
displays the given string `s`, followed by a space character, followed by the
value `v` in the console.
If second argument not present,
just displays the value `v` in the console.
The notation used for the display of values
is consistent with
[JSON](http://www.ecma-international.org/publications/files/ECMA-ST/ECMA-404.pdf),
but also displays `undefined`, `NaN`, `Infinity`, and function objects.

label: display_list
title: display_list(xs, s) → {value}

label: draw_data
title: draw_data() → {value}
description:
#### draw\_data() → {value}

visualizes the arguments in a separate drawing
area in the Source Academy using box-and-pointer diagrams; time, space:
`Theta(n)`, where `n` is the total number of data structures such as
pairs in the arguments.

label: enum_list
title: enum_list(start, end) → {list}
description:
#### enum\_list(start, end) → {list}

Returns a list that enumerates
numbers starting from `start` using a step size of 1, until
the number exceeds (`>`) `end`.
Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)`, space: `Theta(n)`,
where `n` is `end - start`.

label: enum_stream
title: enum_stream(start, end) → {stream}
description:
#### enum\_stream(start, end) → {stream}

Returns a stream that enumerates
numbers starting from `start` using a step size of 1, until
the number exceeds (`>`) `end`.
Lazy? Yes: The result stream forces the construction of
each next element

label: equal
title: equal(x, y) → {boolean}
description:
#### equal(x, y) → {boolean}

Returns `true` if both
have the same structure with respect to `pair`,
and identical values at corresponding leave positions (places that are not
themselves pairs), and `false` otherwise. For the "identical",
the values need to have the same type, otherwise the result is
`false`. If corresponding leaves are boolean values, these values
need to be the same. If both are `undefined` or both are
`null`, the result is `true`. Otherwise they are compared
with `===` (using the definition of `===` in the
respective Source language in use).
Time, space:
`Theta(n)`, where `n` is the total number of data structures such as
pairs in `x` and `y`.

label: error
title: error(v, s)
description:
#### error(v, s)

Optional second argument.
If present,
displays the given string `s`, followed by a space character, followed by the
value `v` in the console with error flag.
If second argument not present,
just displays the value `v` in the console with error flag.
The evaluation
of any call of `error` aborts the running program immediately.
The notation used for the display of values
is consistent with
[JSON](http://www.ecma-international.org/publications/files/ECMA-ST/ECMA-404.pdf),
but also displays `undefined`, `NaN`, `Infinity`, and function objects.

label: eval_stream
title: eval_stream(s, n) → {list}
description:
#### eval\_stream(s, n) → {list}

Constructs the list of the first `n` elements
of a given stream `s`
Lazy? Sort-of: `eval_stream` only forces the computation of
the first `n` elements, and leaves the rest of
the stream untouched.

label: filter
title: filter(pred, xs) → {list}
description:
#### filter(pred, xs) → {list}

Returns a list that contains
only those elements for which the one-argument function
`pred`
returns `true`.
Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)` (apart from `pred`), space: `Theta(n)` (apart from `pred`),
where `n` is the length of `xs`.

label: for_each
title: for_each(f, xs) → {boolean}
description:
#### for\_each(f, xs) → {boolean}

Applies unary function `f` to every
element of the list `xs`.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`), space: `Theta(1)` (apart from `f`),
where `n` is the length of `xs`.
`f` is applied element-by-element:
`for_each(fun, list(1, 2))` results in the calls
`fun(1)` and `fun(2)`.

label: get_time
title: get_time() → {number}

label: head
title: head(p) → {value}
description:
#### head(p) → {value}

\*\*primitive\*\*; returns head (first component) of given pair `p`; time: `Theta(1)Theta(1)`.

label: integers_from
title: integers_from(start) → {stream}
description:
#### integers\_from(start) → {stream}

Returns infinite stream if integers starting
at given number `n` using a step size of 1.
Lazy? Yes: The result stream forces the construction of
each next element

label: is_array
title: is_array(x) → {boolean}
description:
#### is\_array(x) → {boolean}

\*\*primitive\*\*; returns `true` if `x`
is an array, and `false` if it is not.
Time: `Θ(1)`, space: `Θ(1)`

label: is_boolean
title: is_boolean(v) → {boolean}
description:
#### is\_boolean(v) → {boolean}

checks whether a given value is a boolean

label: is_function
title: is_function(v) → {boolean}
description:
#### is\_function(v) → {boolean}

checks whether a given value is a function

label: is_list
title: is_list(xs) → {xs}
description:
#### is\_list(xs) → {xs}

\*\*primitive\*\*; returns `true` if
`xs` is a list as defined in the textbook, and
`false` otherwise. Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)`, space: `Theta(1)`, where `n`
is the length of the
chain of `tail` operations that can be applied to `xs`.
`is_list` recurses down the list and checks that it ends with the empty list null

label: is_null
title: is_null(x) → {boolean}

label: is_number
title: is_number(v) → {boolean}

label: is_pair
title: is_pair(x) → {boolean}

label: is_stream
title: is_stream(xs) → {boolean}
description:
#### is\_stream(xs) → {boolean}

Returns `true` if
`xs` is a stream as defined in the textbook, and
`false` otherwise. Iterative process.
Recurses down the stream and checks that it ends with the empty stream null.
Laziness: No: `is_stream` needs to force the given stream.

label: is_string
title: is_string(v) → {boolean}

label: is_undefined
title: is_undefined(v) → {boolean}
description:
#### is\_undefined(v) → {boolean}

checks whether a given value is the special value `undefined`

label: length
title: length(xs) → {number}
description:
#### length(xs) → {number}

Returns the length of the list
`xs`.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)`, space:
`Theta(1)`, where `n` is the length of `xs`.

label: list
title: list() → {list}

label: list_ref
title: list_ref(xs, n) → {value}
description:
#### list\_ref(xs, n) → {value}

Returns the element
of list `xs` at position `n`,
where the first element has index 0.
Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)`, space: `Theta(1)`,
where `n` is the length of `xs`.

label: list_to_stream
title: list_to_stream(xs) → {stream}
description:
#### list\_to\_stream(xs) → {stream}

Given list `xs`, returns a stream of same length with
the same elements as `xs` in the same order.
Laziness: Yes: `list_to_stream`
goes down the list only when forced.

label: list_to_string
title: list_to_string(xs) → {string}
description:
#### list\_to\_string(xs) → {string}

Returns a string that represents
list `xs` using the text-based box-and-pointer notation
`[...]`.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)` where `n` is the size of the list, space: `Theta(m)` where `m` is the length of the string.
The process is iterative, but consumes space `O(m)`
because of the result string.

label: map
title: map(f, xs) → {list}
description:
#### map(f, xs) → {list}

Returns a list that results from list
`xs` by element-wise application of unary function `f`.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`),
space: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`), where `n` is the length of `xs`.
`f` is applied element-by-element:
`map(f, list(1, 2))` results in `list(f(1), f(2))`.

label: math_abs
title: math_abs(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_abs(x) → {number}

computes the absolute value of x; the result has the same magnitude as `x` but has positive sign.

label: math_acos
title: math_acos(x) → {number}

label: math_acosh
title: math_acosh(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_acosh(x) → {number}

computes the inverse hyperbolic cosine of `x`.

label: math_asin
title: math_asin(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_asin(x) → {number}

computes the arc sine of `x`. The result is expressed in radians and ranges from -π / 2 to +π / 2.

label: math_asinh
title: math_asinh(x) → {number}

label: math_atan
title: math_atan(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_atan(x) → {number}

computes the arc tangent of `x`. The result is expressed in radians and ranges from -π / 2 to +π / 2.

label: math_atan2
title: math_atan2(y, x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_atan2(y, x) → {number}

computes the arc tangent of the quotient `y` / `x` of the arguments `y` and `x`, where the signs of `y` and `x` are used to determine the quadrant of the result. Note that it is intentional and traditional for the two-argument arc tangent function that the argument named `y` be first and the argument named `x` be second. The result is expressed in radians and ranges from -π to +π.

label: math_atanh
title: math_atanh(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_atanh(x) → {number}

computes the inverse hyperbolic tangent of `x`.

label: math_cbrt
title: math_cbrt(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_cbrt(x) → {number}

computes the cube root of `x`.

label: math_ceil
title: math_ceil(x) → {number}

label: math_clz32
title: math_clz32(n) → {number}
description:
#### math\_clz32(n) → {number}

When math\_clz32 is called with one argument `x`, the following steps are taken:
Let n be ToUint32(x).
Let p be the number of leading zero bits in the 32-bit binary representation of n.
Return p.

NOTE:
  
If n is 0, p will be 32. If the most significant bit of the 32-bit binary encoding of n is 1,
p will be 0.

label: math_cos
title: math_cos(x) → {number}

label: math_cosh
title: math_cosh(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_cosh(x) → {number}

computes the hyperbolic cosine of `x`.

NOTE:
The value of cosh(x) is the same as (exp(x) + exp(-x)) / 2.

label: math_exp
title: math_exp(x) → {number}

label: math_expm1
title: math_expm1(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_expm1(x) → {number}

computes subtracting 1 from the
exponential function of `x` (e raised to the power of `x`, where e is the base of
the natural logarithms). The result is computed in a way that is accurate even
when the value of `x` is close to 0.

label: math_floor
title: math_floor(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_floor(x) → {number}

computes the greatest (closest to +∞) Number value that is not greater than `x`
and is an integer.
  
If `x` is already an integer, the result is `x`.

NOTE:
The value of math\_floor(x) is the same as the value of -math\_ceil(-x).

label: math_fround
title: math_fround(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_fround(x) → {number}

When math\_fround is called with argument `x`, the following steps are taken:

1. If `x` is NaN, return NaN.
2. If `x` is one of +0, -0, +∞, -∞, return `x`.
3. Let x32 be the result of converting `x` to a value in IEEE 754-2008 binary32 format using roundTiesToEven mode.
4. Let x64 be the result of converting x32 to a value in IEEE 754-2008 binary64 format.
5. Return the ECMAScript Number value corresponding to x64.

label: math_hypot
title: math_hypot() → {number}
description:
#### math\_hypot() → {number}

computes the square root
of the sum of squares of its arguments.
  
If no arguments are passed, the result is +0.

label: math_imul
title: math_imul(x, x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_imul(x, x) → {number}

When math\_imul is called with arguments `x` and `y`,
the following steps are taken:

1. Let a be ToUint32(x).
2. Let b be ToUint32(y).
3. Let product be (a × b) modulo 232.
4. If product ≥ 231, return product - 232; otherwise return product.

label: math_log
title: math_log(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_log(x) → {number}

Computes the natural logarithm of `x`.

label: math_log1p
title: math_log1p(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_log1p(x) → {number}

computes the natural logarithm of 1 + `x`. The result is computed in a way that is accurate even when the value of `x` is close to zero.

label: math_log2
title: math_log2(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_log2(x) → {number}

computes the base 2 logarithm of `x`.

label: math_log10
title: math_log10(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_log10(x) → {number}

computes the base 10 logarithm of `x`.

label: math_max
title: math_max() → {number}
description:
#### math\_max() → {number}

Given zero or more numbers, returns the largest of them.
  
If no arguments are given, the result is -∞.
  
If any value is NaN, the result is NaN.
The comparison of values to determine the largest value is done using the
Abstract Relational Comparison algorithm except that +0 is considered to be larger than -0.

label: math_min
title: math_min() → {number}
description:
#### math\_min() → {number}

Given zero or more arguments, returns the smallest of them.
  
If no arguments are given, the result is +∞.
  
If any value is NaN, the result is NaN.
The comparison of values to determine the smallest value is done using the
Abstract Relational Comparison algorithm except that +0 is considered to be larger than -0.

label: math_pow
title: math_pow(base, exponent) → {number}

label: math_random
title: math_random() → {number}
description:
#### math\_random() → {number}

Returns a number value with positive sign, greater than or equal to 0 but less than 1,
chosen randomly or pseudo randomly with approximately uniform distribution over that
range, using an implementation-dependent algorithm or strategy. This function takes no arguments.
Each math\_random function created for distinct realms must produce a distinct sequence
of values from successive calls.

label: math_round
title: math_round(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_round(x) → {number}

Returns the number value that is closest to `x` and is an integer.
  
If two integers are equally close to `x`, then the result is the Number value
that is closer to +∞. If `x` is already an integer, the result is `x`.
NOTE 1:
math\_round(3.5) returns 4, but math\_round(-3.5) returns -3.

label: math_sign
title: math_sign(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_sign(x) → {number}

Computes the sign of `x`, indicating whether `x` is positive, negative, or zero.

label: math_sin
title: math_sin(x) → {number}

label: math_sinh
title: math_sinh(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_sinh(x) → {number}

Computes the hyperbolic sine of `x`.

NOTE:
The value of sinh(x) is the same as (exp(x) - exp(-x)) / 2.

label: math_sqrt
title: math_sqrt(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_sqrt(x) → {number}

Computes the square root of `x`.

label: math_tan
title: math_tan(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_tan(x) → {number}

Computes the tangent of `x`. The argument is expressed in radians.

label: math_tanh
title: math_tanh(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_tanh(x) → {number}

Computes the hyperbolic tangent of `x`.

NOTE:
The value of `math_tanh(x)` is the same as
`(exp(x) - exp(-x))/(exp(x) + exp(-x))`.

label: math_trunc
title: math_trunc(x) → {number}

label: member
title: member(v, xs) → {list}
description:
#### member(v, xs) → {list}

Returns first postfix sublist
whose head is identical to
`v` (using `===`); returns `null` if the
element does not occur in the list.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)`,
space: `Theta(1)`, where `n` is the length of `xs`.

label: pair
title: pair(x, y) → {pair}

label: parse_int
title: parse_int(s, i) → {number}
description:
#### parse\_int(s, i) → {number}

Interprets a given string `s` as an integer,
using the positive integer `i` as radix,
and returns the respective value.
  
Examples: `parse_int("909", 10)` returns the number
`909`, and `parse_int("-1111", 2)` returns the number
`-15`.  

See [ECMAScript Specification, Section 18.2.5](https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/9.0/index.html#sec-parseint-string-radix) for details.

label: prompt
title: prompt(s) → {string}
description:
#### prompt(s) → {string}

Pops up a window that displays the string `s`, provides
an input line for the user to enter a text, a `Cancel` button and an `OK` button.
The call of `prompt`
suspends execution of the program until one of the two buttons is pressed. If
the `OK` button is pressed, `prompt` returns the entered text as a string.
If the `Cancel` button is pressed, `prompt` returns a non-string value.

label: remove
title: remove(v, xs) → {list}
description:
#### remove(v, xs) → {list}

Returns a list that results from
`xs` by removing the first item from `xs` that
is identical (`===`) to `v`.
Returns the original
list if there is no occurrence. Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)`, space: `Theta(n)`, where `n`
is the length of `xs`.

label: remove_all
title: remove_all(v, xs) → {list}
description:
#### remove\_all(v, xs) → {list}

Returns a list that results from
`xs` by removing all items from `xs` that
are identical (`===`) to `v`.
Returns the original
list if there is no occurrence.
Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)`, space: `Theta(n)`, where `n`
is the length of `xs`.

label: reverse
title: reverse(xs) → {list}
description:
#### reverse(xs) → {list}

Returns list `xs` in reverse
order. Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)`,
space: `Theta(n)`, where `n` is the length of `xs`.
The process is iterative, but consumes space `Theta(n)`
because of the result list.

label: set_head
title: set_head(p, x) → {undefined}
description:
#### set\_head(p, x) → {undefined}

changes the pair `p` such that its head is `x`.

label: set_tail
title: set_tail(p, x) → {undefined}
description:
#### set\_tail(p, x) → {undefined}

changes the pair `p` such that its tail is `x`.

label: stream
title: stream() → {stream}
description:
#### stream() → {stream}

Given `n` values, returns a stream of length `n`.
The elements of the stream are the given values in the given order.
Lazy? No: A
complete list is generated,
and then a stream using `list_to_stream` is generated from it.

label: stream_append
title: stream_append(xs, ys) → {stream}
description:
#### stream\_append(xs, ys) → {stream}

Returns a stream that results from
appending the stream `ys` to the stream `xs`.
In the result, null at the end of the first argument stream
is replaced by the second argument, regardless what the second
argument consists of.
Lazy? Yes: the result stream forces the actual append operation

label: stream_filter
title: stream_filter(pred, xs) → {stream}
description:
#### stream\_filter(pred, xs) → {stream}

Returns a stream that contains
only those elements of given stream `xs`
for which the one-argument function
`pred`
returns `true`.
Lazy? Yes: The result stream forces the construction of
each next element. Of course, the construction
of the next element needs to go down the stream
until an element is found for which `pred` holds.

label: stream_for_each
title: stream_for_each(f, xs) → {boolean}
description:
#### stream\_for\_each(f, xs) → {boolean}

Applies unary function `f` to every
element of the stream `xs`.
Iterative process.
`f` is applied element-by-element:
`stream_for_each(f, stream(1, 2))` results in the calls
`f(1)` and `f(2)`.
Lazy? No: `stream_for_each`
forces the exploration of the entire stream

label: stream_length
title: stream_length(xs) → {number}
description:
#### stream\_length(xs) → {number}

Returns the length of the stream
`xs`.
Iterative process.
Lazy? No: The function needs to explore the whole stream

label: stream_map
title: stream_map(f, xs) → {stream}
description:
#### stream\_map(f, xs) → {stream}

Returns a stream that results from stream
`xs` by element-wise application
of unary function `f`.
`f` is applied element-by-element:
`stream_map(f, stream(1,2))` results in
the same as `stream(f(1),f(2))`.
Lazy? Yes: The argument stream is only explored as forced by
the result stream.

label: stream_member
title: stream_member(v, xs) → {stream}
description:
#### stream\_member(v, xs) → {stream}

Returns first postfix substream
whose head is identical to
`v` (using `===`); returns `null` if the
element does not occur in the stream.
Iterative process.
Lazy? Sort-of: `stream_member`
forces the stream only until the element
is found.

label: stream_ref
title: stream_ref(xs, n) → {value}
description:
#### stream\_ref(xs, n) → {value}

Returns the element
of stream `xs` at position `n`,
where the first element has index 0.
Iterative process.
Lazy? Sort-of: `stream_ref` only forces the computation of
the first `n` elements, and leaves the rest of
the stream untouched.

label: stream_remove
title: stream_remove(v, xs) → {stream}
description:
#### stream\_remove(v, xs) → {stream}

Returns a stream that results from
`xs` by removing the first item from `xs` that
is identical (`===`) to `v`.
Returns the original
stream if there is no occurrence.
Lazy? Yes: the result stream forces the construction of each next element

label: stream_remove_all
title: stream_remove_all(v, xs) → {stream}
description:
#### stream\_remove\_all(v, xs) → {stream}

Returns a stream that results from
`xs` by removing all items from `xs` that
are identical (`===`) to `v`.
Returns the original
stream if there is no occurrence.
Recursive process.
Lazy? Yes: the result stream forces the construction of each next
element

label: stream_reverse
title: stream_reverse(xs) → {stream}
description:
#### stream\_reverse(xs) → {stream}

Returns stream `xs` in reverse
order. Iterative process.
The process is iterative, but consumes space `Omega(n)`
because of the result stream.
Lazy? No: `stream_reverse`
forces the exploration of the entire stream

label: stream_tail
title: stream_tail(xs) → {Stream}
description:
#### stream\_tail(xs) → {Stream}

assumes that the tail (second component) of the
pair {x} is a nullary function, and returns the result of
applying that function. Throws an exception if the argument
is not a pair, or if the tail is not a function.
Laziness: Yes: {stream\_tail} only forces the direct tail
stream, but not the rest of the stream, i.e. not the tail
of the tail, etc.

label: stream_to_list
title: stream_to_list(xs) → {list}
description:
#### stream\_to\_list(xs) → {list}

Given stream `xs`, returns a list of same length with
the same elements as `xs` in the same order.
Laziness: No: `stream_to_list` needs to force the whole
stream.

label: stringify
title: stringify(v) → {string}
description:
#### stringify(v) → {string}

returns a string that represents the value `v`, using a
notation that is is consistent with
[JSON](http://www.ecma-international.org/publications/files/ECMA-ST/ECMA-404.pdf),
but also displays `undefined`, `NaN`, `Infinity`, and function objects.
See also [textbook example](https://sourceacademy.org/sicpjs/3.3.5).

label: tail
title: tail(p) → {value}
description:
#### tail(p) → {value}

\*\*primitive\*\*; returns tail (second component of given pair `p`; time: `Theta(1)Theta(1)`.

label: Infinity
title: Infinity:number
description:
#### Infinity:number

The name `Infinity` refers to the special number value `Infinity`.
See [ECMAScript Specification, Section 4.3.23](https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/9.0/index.html#sec-value-properties-of-the-global-object-infinity)

label: math_E
title: math_E:number
description:
#### math\_E:number

The Number value for e, Euler's number,
which is approximately 2.718281828459045.

label: math_LN2
title: math_LN2:number
description:
#### math\_LN2:number

The Number value for the natural logarithm of 2,
which is approximately 0.6931471805599453.

label: math_LN10
title: math_LN10:number
description:
#### math\_LN10:number

The Number value for the natural logarithm of 10,
which is approximately 2.302585092994046.

label: math_LOG2E
title: math_LOG2E:number
description:
#### math\_LOG2E:number

The Number value for the base-2 logarithm of eℝ, the base of the natural logarithms;
this value is approximately 1.4426950408889634.

NOTE:
The value of math\_LOG2E is approximately the reciprocal of the value of math\_LN2.

label: math_LOG10E
title: math_LOG10E:number
description:
#### math\_LOG10E:number

The Number value for the base-10 logarithm of e,
the base of the natural logarithms; this value is approximately 0.4342944819032518.

NOTE:
The value of math\_LOG10E is approximately the reciprocal of the value of math\_LN10.

label: math_PI
title: math_PI:number
description:
#### math\_PI:number

The Number value for π, the ratio of the circumference of a circle to its diameter,
which is approximately 3.1415926535897932.

label: math_SQRT1_2
title: math_SQRT1_2:number
description:
#### math\_SQRT1\_2:number

The Number value for the square root of 0.5, which is approximately 0.7071067811865476.

NOTE:
The value of math\_SQRT1\_2 is approximately the reciprocal of the value of math\_SQRT2.

label: math_SQRT2
title: math_SQRT2:number
description:
#### math\_SQRT2:number

The Number value for the square root of 2, which is approximately 1.4142135623730951.

label: NaN
title: NaN:number
description:
#### NaN:number

The name `NaN` refers to the special number value `NaN` ("not a number"). Note that
`NaN` is a number, as specified by `is_number`.
See [ECMAScript Specification, Section 4.3.24](https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/9.0/index.html#sec-value-properties-of-the-global-object-nan)

label: undefined
title: undefined:undefined
description:
#### undefined:undefined

The name `undefined` refers to the special value `undefined`.
See also [textbook explanation in section 4.1.1](https://sourceacademy.org/sicpjs/4.1.1#h5).

label: __access_export__
title: __access_export__(exports, lookup_name) → {value}
description:
#### \_\_access\_export\_\_(exports, lookup\_name) → {value}

Searches for the specified name in the data structure of exported names.
The data structure is a pair where the head element is the default export
and the tail element is a list of pairs where each pair is a mapping from
the exported name to the value being exported. If the lookup name is
"default", the default export is returned instead of a named export. If
the name does not exist, `undefined` is returned.

label: __access_named_export__
title: __access_named_export__(named_exports, lookup_name) → {value}
description:
#### \_\_access\_named\_export\_\_(named\_exports, lookup\_name) → {value}

Searches for the specified name in the data structure of exported names.
The data structure is a list of pairs where each pair is a mapping from
the exported name to the value being exported. If the name does not exist,
`undefined` is returned.

label: accumulate
title: accumulate(f, initial, xs) → {value}
description:
#### accumulate(f, initial, xs) → {value}

Applies binary
function `f` to the elements of `xs` from
right-to-left order, first applying `f` to the last element
and the value `initial`, resulting in `r`1,
then to the
second-last element and `r`1, resulting in
`r`2,
etc, and finally
to the first element and `r`n-1, where
`n` is the length of the
list. Thus, `accumulate(f,zero,list(1,2,3))` results in
`f(1, f(2, f(3, zero)))`.
Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`), space: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`),
where `n` is the length of `xs`.

label: append
title: append(xs, ys) → {list}
description:
#### append(xs, ys) → {list}

Returns a list that results from
appending the list `ys` to the list `xs`.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)`, space:
`Theta(n)`, where `n` is the length of `xs`.
In the result, null at the end of the first argument list
is replaced by the second argument, regardless what the second
argument consists of.

label: apply_in_underlying_javascript
title: apply_in_underlying_javascript(f, xs) → {whatever}

label: arity
title: arity(f) → {number}

label: array_length
title: array_length(x) → {number}
description:
#### array\_length(x) → {number}

\*\*primitive\*\*; returns
the current length of array `x`, which is 1 plus the
highest index that has been used so far in an array assignment on
`x`. Here literal array expressions are counted too: The
array `[10, 20, 30]` has a length of 3.
Time: `Θ(1)`, space: `Θ(1)`

label: build_list
title: build_list(f, n) → {list}
description:
#### build\_list(f, n) → {list}

Makes a list with `n`
elements by applying the unary function `f`
to the numbers 0 to `n - 1`, assumed to be a nonnegative integer.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`), space: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`).

label: build_stream
title: build_stream(f, n) → {stream}
description:
#### build\_stream(f, n) → {stream}

Makes a stream with `n`
elements by applying the unary function `f`
to the numbers 0 to `n - 1`, assumed to be a nonnegative integer.
Lazy? Yes: The result stream forces the application of `f`
for the next element

label: char_at
title: char_at(s, i) → {string}
description:
#### char\_at(s, i) → {string}

Takes a string `s` as first argument and a nonnegative integer
`i` as second argument. If `i` is less than the length
of `s`, this function returns a one-character string that contains
the character of `s` at position `i`, counting from 0.
If `i` is larger than or equal to the length of
`s`, this function returns `undefined`.

label: display
title: display(v, s) → {value}
description:
#### display(v, s) → {value}

Optional second argument. If present,
displays the given string `s`, followed by a space character, followed by the
value `v` in the console.
If second argument not present,
just displays the value `v` in the console.
The notation used for the display of values
is consistent with
[JSON](http://www.ecma-international.org/publications/files/ECMA-ST/ECMA-404.pdf),
but also displays `undefined`, `NaN`, `Infinity`, and function objects.

label: display_list
title: display_list(xs, s) → {value}

label: draw_data
title: draw_data() → {value}
description:
#### draw\_data() → {value}

visualizes the arguments in a separate drawing
area in the Source Academy using box-and-pointer diagrams; time, space:
`Theta(n)`, where `n` is the total number of data structures such as
pairs in the arguments.

label: enum_list
title: enum_list(start, end) → {list}
description:
#### enum\_list(start, end) → {list}

Returns a list that enumerates
numbers starting from `start` using a step size of 1, until
the number exceeds (`>`) `end`.
Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)`, space: `Theta(n)`,
where `n` is `end - start`.

label: enum_stream
title: enum_stream(start, end) → {stream}
description:
#### enum\_stream(start, end) → {stream}

Returns a stream that enumerates
numbers starting from `start` using a step size of 1, until
the number exceeds (`>`) `end`.
Lazy? Yes: The result stream forces the construction of
each next element

label: equal
title: equal(x, y) → {boolean}
description:
#### equal(x, y) → {boolean}

Returns `true` if both
have the same structure with respect to `pair`,
and identical values at corresponding leave positions (places that are not
themselves pairs), and `false` otherwise. For the "identical",
the values need to have the same type, otherwise the result is
`false`. If corresponding leaves are boolean values, these values
need to be the same. If both are `undefined` or both are
`null`, the result is `true`. Otherwise they are compared
with `===` (using the definition of `===` in the
respective Source language in use).
Time, space:
`Theta(n)`, where `n` is the total number of data structures such as
pairs in `x` and `y`.

label: error
title: error(v, s)
description:
#### error(v, s)

Optional second argument.
If present,
displays the given string `s`, followed by a space character, followed by the
value `v` in the console with error flag.
If second argument not present,
just displays the value `v` in the console with error flag.
The evaluation
of any call of `error` aborts the running program immediately.
The notation used for the display of values
is consistent with
[JSON](http://www.ecma-international.org/publications/files/ECMA-ST/ECMA-404.pdf),
but also displays `undefined`, `NaN`, `Infinity`, and function objects.

label: eval_stream
title: eval_stream(s, n) → {list}
description:
#### eval\_stream(s, n) → {list}

Constructs the list of the first `n` elements
of a given stream `s`
Lazy? Sort-of: `eval_stream` only forces the computation of
the first `n` elements, and leaves the rest of
the stream untouched.

label: filter
title: filter(pred, xs) → {list}
description:
#### filter(pred, xs) → {list}

Returns a list that contains
only those elements for which the one-argument function
`pred`
returns `true`.
Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)` (apart from `pred`), space: `Theta(n)` (apart from `pred`),
where `n` is the length of `xs`.

label: for_each
title: for_each(f, xs) → {boolean}
description:
#### for\_each(f, xs) → {boolean}

Applies unary function `f` to every
element of the list `xs`.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`), space: `Theta(1)` (apart from `f`),
where `n` is the length of `xs`.
`f` is applied element-by-element:
`for_each(fun, list(1, 2))` results in the calls
`fun(1)` and `fun(2)`.

label: get_time
title: get_time() → {number}

label: head
title: head(p) → {value}
description:
#### head(p) → {value}

\*\*primitive\*\*; returns head (first component) of given pair `p`; time: `Theta(1)Theta(1)`.

label: integers_from
title: integers_from(start) → {stream}
description:
#### integers\_from(start) → {stream}

Returns infinite stream if integers starting
at given number `n` using a step size of 1.
Lazy? Yes: The result stream forces the construction of
each next element

label: is_array
title: is_array(x) → {boolean}
description:
#### is\_array(x) → {boolean}

\*\*primitive\*\*; returns `true` if `x`
is an array, and `false` if it is not.
Time: `Θ(1)`, space: `Θ(1)`

label: is_boolean
title: is_boolean(v) → {boolean}
description:
#### is\_boolean(v) → {boolean}

checks whether a given value is a boolean

label: is_function
title: is_function(v) → {boolean}
description:
#### is\_function(v) → {boolean}

checks whether a given value is a function

label: is_list
title: is_list(xs) → {xs}
description:
#### is\_list(xs) → {xs}

\*\*primitive\*\*; returns `true` if
`xs` is a list as defined in the textbook, and
`false` otherwise. Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)`, space: `Theta(1)`, where `n`
is the length of the
chain of `tail` operations that can be applied to `xs`.
`is_list` recurses down the list and checks that it ends with the empty list null

label: is_null
title: is_null(x) → {boolean}

label: is_number
title: is_number(v) → {boolean}

label: is_pair
title: is_pair(x) → {boolean}

label: is_stream
title: is_stream(xs) → {boolean}
description:
#### is\_stream(xs) → {boolean}

Returns `true` if
`xs` is a stream as defined in the textbook, and
`false` otherwise. Iterative process.
Recurses down the stream and checks that it ends with the empty stream null.
Laziness: No: `is_stream` needs to force the given stream.

label: is_string
title: is_string(v) → {boolean}

label: is_undefined
title: is_undefined(v) → {boolean}
description:
#### is\_undefined(v) → {boolean}

checks whether a given value is the special value `undefined`

label: length
title: length(xs) → {number}
description:
#### length(xs) → {number}

Returns the length of the list
`xs`.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)`, space:
`Theta(1)`, where `n` is the length of `xs`.

label: list
title: list() → {list}

label: list_ref
title: list_ref(xs, n) → {value}
description:
#### list\_ref(xs, n) → {value}

Returns the element
of list `xs` at position `n`,
where the first element has index 0.
Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)`, space: `Theta(1)`,
where `n` is the length of `xs`.

label: list_to_stream
title: list_to_stream(xs) → {stream}
description:
#### list\_to\_stream(xs) → {stream}

Given list `xs`, returns a stream of same length with
the same elements as `xs` in the same order.
Laziness: Yes: `list_to_stream`
goes down the list only when forced.

label: list_to_string
title: list_to_string(xs) → {string}
description:
#### list\_to\_string(xs) → {string}

Returns a string that represents
list `xs` using the text-based box-and-pointer notation
`[...]`.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)` where `n` is the size of the list, space: `Theta(m)` where `m` is the length of the string.
The process is iterative, but consumes space `O(m)`
because of the result string.

label: map
title: map(f, xs) → {list}
description:
#### map(f, xs) → {list}

Returns a list that results from list
`xs` by element-wise application of unary function `f`.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`),
space: `Theta(n)` (apart from `f`), where `n` is the length of `xs`.
`f` is applied element-by-element:
`map(f, list(1, 2))` results in `list(f(1), f(2))`.

label: math_abs
title: math_abs(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_abs(x) → {number}

computes the absolute value of x; the result has the same magnitude as `x` but has positive sign.

label: math_acos
title: math_acos(x) → {number}

label: math_acosh
title: math_acosh(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_acosh(x) → {number}

computes the inverse hyperbolic cosine of `x`.

label: math_asin
title: math_asin(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_asin(x) → {number}

computes the arc sine of `x`. The result is expressed in radians and ranges from -π / 2 to +π / 2.

label: math_asinh
title: math_asinh(x) → {number}

label: math_atan
title: math_atan(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_atan(x) → {number}

computes the arc tangent of `x`. The result is expressed in radians and ranges from -π / 2 to +π / 2.

label: math_atan2
title: math_atan2(y, x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_atan2(y, x) → {number}

computes the arc tangent of the quotient `y` / `x` of the arguments `y` and `x`, where the signs of `y` and `x` are used to determine the quadrant of the result. Note that it is intentional and traditional for the two-argument arc tangent function that the argument named `y` be first and the argument named `x` be second. The result is expressed in radians and ranges from -π to +π.

label: math_atanh
title: math_atanh(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_atanh(x) → {number}

computes the inverse hyperbolic tangent of `x`.

label: math_cbrt
title: math_cbrt(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_cbrt(x) → {number}

computes the cube root of `x`.

label: math_ceil
title: math_ceil(x) → {number}

label: math_clz32
title: math_clz32(n) → {number}
description:
#### math\_clz32(n) → {number}

When math\_clz32 is called with one argument `x`, the following steps are taken:
Let n be ToUint32(x).
Let p be the number of leading zero bits in the 32-bit binary representation of n.
Return p.

NOTE:
  
If n is 0, p will be 32. If the most significant bit of the 32-bit binary encoding of n is 1,
p will be 0.

label: math_cos
title: math_cos(x) → {number}

label: math_cosh
title: math_cosh(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_cosh(x) → {number}

computes the hyperbolic cosine of `x`.

NOTE:
The value of cosh(x) is the same as (exp(x) + exp(-x)) / 2.

label: math_exp
title: math_exp(x) → {number}

label: math_expm1
title: math_expm1(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_expm1(x) → {number}

computes subtracting 1 from the
exponential function of `x` (e raised to the power of `x`, where e is the base of
the natural logarithms). The result is computed in a way that is accurate even
when the value of `x` is close to 0.

label: math_floor
title: math_floor(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_floor(x) → {number}

computes the greatest (closest to +∞) Number value that is not greater than `x`
and is an integer.
  
If `x` is already an integer, the result is `x`.

NOTE:
The value of math\_floor(x) is the same as the value of -math\_ceil(-x).

label: math_fround
title: math_fround(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_fround(x) → {number}

When math\_fround is called with argument `x`, the following steps are taken:

1. If `x` is NaN, return NaN.
2. If `x` is one of +0, -0, +∞, -∞, return `x`.
3. Let x32 be the result of converting `x` to a value in IEEE 754-2008 binary32 format using roundTiesToEven mode.
4. Let x64 be the result of converting x32 to a value in IEEE 754-2008 binary64 format.
5. Return the ECMAScript Number value corresponding to x64.

label: math_hypot
title: math_hypot() → {number}
description:
#### math\_hypot() → {number}

computes the square root
of the sum of squares of its arguments.
  
If no arguments are passed, the result is +0.

label: math_imul
title: math_imul(x, x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_imul(x, x) → {number}

When math\_imul is called with arguments `x` and `y`,
the following steps are taken:

1. Let a be ToUint32(x).
2. Let b be ToUint32(y).
3. Let product be (a × b) modulo 232.
4. If product ≥ 231, return product - 232; otherwise return product.

label: math_log
title: math_log(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_log(x) → {number}

Computes the natural logarithm of `x`.

label: math_log1p
title: math_log1p(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_log1p(x) → {number}

computes the natural logarithm of 1 + `x`. The result is computed in a way that is accurate even when the value of `x` is close to zero.

label: math_log2
title: math_log2(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_log2(x) → {number}

computes the base 2 logarithm of `x`.

label: math_log10
title: math_log10(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_log10(x) → {number}

computes the base 10 logarithm of `x`.

label: math_max
title: math_max() → {number}
description:
#### math\_max() → {number}

Given zero or more numbers, returns the largest of them.
  
If no arguments are given, the result is -∞.
  
If any value is NaN, the result is NaN.
The comparison of values to determine the largest value is done using the
Abstract Relational Comparison algorithm except that +0 is considered to be larger than -0.

label: math_min
title: math_min() → {number}
description:
#### math\_min() → {number}

Given zero or more arguments, returns the smallest of them.
  
If no arguments are given, the result is +∞.
  
If any value is NaN, the result is NaN.
The comparison of values to determine the smallest value is done using the
Abstract Relational Comparison algorithm except that +0 is considered to be larger than -0.

label: math_pow
title: math_pow(base, exponent) → {number}

label: math_random
title: math_random() → {number}
description:
#### math\_random() → {number}

Returns a number value with positive sign, greater than or equal to 0 but less than 1,
chosen randomly or pseudo randomly with approximately uniform distribution over that
range, using an implementation-dependent algorithm or strategy. This function takes no arguments.
Each math\_random function created for distinct realms must produce a distinct sequence
of values from successive calls.

label: math_round
title: math_round(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_round(x) → {number}

Returns the number value that is closest to `x` and is an integer.
  
If two integers are equally close to `x`, then the result is the Number value
that is closer to +∞. If `x` is already an integer, the result is `x`.
NOTE 1:
math\_round(3.5) returns 4, but math\_round(-3.5) returns -3.

label: math_sign
title: math_sign(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_sign(x) → {number}

Computes the sign of `x`, indicating whether `x` is positive, negative, or zero.

label: math_sin
title: math_sin(x) → {number}

label: math_sinh
title: math_sinh(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_sinh(x) → {number}

Computes the hyperbolic sine of `x`.

NOTE:
The value of sinh(x) is the same as (exp(x) - exp(-x)) / 2.

label: math_sqrt
title: math_sqrt(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_sqrt(x) → {number}

Computes the square root of `x`.

label: math_tan
title: math_tan(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_tan(x) → {number}

Computes the tangent of `x`. The argument is expressed in radians.

label: math_tanh
title: math_tanh(x) → {number}
description:
#### math\_tanh(x) → {number}

Computes the hyperbolic tangent of `x`.

NOTE:
The value of `math_tanh(x)` is the same as
`(exp(x) - exp(-x))/(exp(x) + exp(-x))`.

label: math_trunc
title: math_trunc(x) → {number}

label: member
title: member(v, xs) → {list}
description:
#### member(v, xs) → {list}

Returns first postfix sublist
whose head is identical to
`v` (using `===`); returns `null` if the
element does not occur in the list.
Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)`,
space: `Theta(1)`, where `n` is the length of `xs`.

label: pair
title: pair(x, y) → {pair}

label: parse
title: parse(x) → {value}
description:
#### parse(x) → {value}

returns the parse tree that results from parsing
the string `str` as a Source program. The format
of the parse tree is described in chapter 4 of
the textbook
in [Structure and
Interpretation of Computer Programs, JavaScript Adaptation](https://sourceacademy.org/sicpjs/) (SICP).

label: parse_int
title: parse_int(s, i) → {number}
description:
#### parse\_int(s, i) → {number}

Interprets a given string `s` as an integer,
using the positive integer `i` as radix,
and returns the respective value.
  
Examples: `parse_int("909", 10)` returns the number
`909`, and `parse_int("-1111", 2)` returns the number
`-15`.  

See [ECMAScript Specification, Section 18.2.5](https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/9.0/index.html#sec-parseint-string-radix) for details.

label: prompt
title: prompt(s) → {string}
description:
#### prompt(s) → {string}

Pops up a window that displays the string `s`, provides
an input line for the user to enter a text, a `Cancel` button and an `OK` button.
The call of `prompt`
suspends execution of the program until one of the two buttons is pressed. If
the `OK` button is pressed, `prompt` returns the entered text as a string.
If the `Cancel` button is pressed, `prompt` returns a non-string value.

label: remove
title: remove(v, xs) → {list}
description:
#### remove(v, xs) → {list}

Returns a list that results from
`xs` by removing the first item from `xs` that
is identical (`===`) to `v`.
Returns the original
list if there is no occurrence. Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)`, space: `Theta(n)`, where `n`
is the length of `xs`.

label: remove_all
title: remove_all(v, xs) → {list}
description:
#### remove\_all(v, xs) → {list}

Returns a list that results from
`xs` by removing all items from `xs` that
are identical (`===`) to `v`.
Returns the original
list if there is no occurrence.
Iterative process;
time: `Theta(n)`, space: `Theta(n)`, where `n`
is the length of `xs`.

label: reverse
title: reverse(xs) → {list}
description:
#### reverse(xs) → {list}

Returns list `xs` in reverse
order. Iterative process; time: `Theta(n)`,
space: `Theta(n)`, where `n` is the length of `xs`.
The process is iterative, but consumes space `Theta(n)`
because of the result list.

label: set_head
title: set_head(p, x) → {undefined}
description:
#### set\_head(p, x) → {undefined}

changes the pair `p` such that its head is `x`.

label: set_tail
title: set_tail(p, x) → {undefined}
description:
#### set\_tail(p, x) → {undefined}

changes the pair `p` such that its tail is `x`.

label: stream
title: stream() → {stream}
description:
#### stream() → {stream}

Given `n` values, returns a stream of length `n`.
The elements of the stream are the given values in the given order.
Lazy? No: A
complete list is generated,
and then a stream using `list_to_stream` is generated from it.

label: stream_append
title: stream_append(xs, ys) → {stream}
description:
#### stream\_append(xs, ys) → {stream}

Returns a stream that results from
appending the stream `ys` to the stream `xs`.
In the result, null at the end of the first argument stream
is replaced by the second argument, regardless what the second
argument consists of.
Lazy? Yes: the result stream forces the actual append operation

label: stream_filter
title: stream_filter(pred, xs) → {stream}
description:
#### stream\_filter(pred, xs) → {stream}

Returns a stream that contains
only those elements of given stream `xs`
for which the one-argument function
`pred`
returns `true`.
Lazy? Yes: The result stream forces the construction of
each next element. Of course, the construction
of the next element needs to go down the stream
until an element is found for which `pred` holds.

label: stream_for_each
title: stream_for_each(f, xs) → {boolean}
description:
#### stream\_for\_each(f, xs) → {boolean}

Applies unary function `f` to every
element of the stream `xs`.
Iterative process.
`f` is applied element-by-element:
`stream_for_each(f, stream(1, 2))` results in the calls
`f(1)` and `f(2)`.
Lazy? No: `stream_for_each`
forces the exploration of the entire stream

label: stream_length
title: stream_length(xs) → {number}
description:
#### stream\_length(xs) → {number}

Returns the length of the stream
`xs`.
Iterative process.
Lazy? No: The function needs to explore the whole stream

label: stream_map
title: stream_map(f, xs) → {stream}
description:
#### stream\_map(f, xs) → {stream}

Returns a stream that results from stream
`xs` by element-wise application
of unary function `f`.
`f` is applied element-by-element:
`stream_map(f, stream(1,2))` results in
the same as `stream(f(1),f(2))`.
Lazy? Yes: The argument stream is only explored as forced by
the result stream.

label: stream_member
title: stream_member(v, xs) → {stream}
description:
#### stream\_member(v, xs) → {stream}

Returns first postfix substream
whose head is identical to
`v` (using `===`); returns `null` if the
element does not occur in the stream.
Iterative process.
Lazy? Sort-of: `stream_member`
forces the stream only until the element
is found.

label: stream_ref
title: stream_ref(xs, n) → {value}
description:
#### stream\_ref(xs, n) → {value}

Returns the element
of stream `xs` at position `n`,
where the first element has index 0.
Iterative process.
Lazy? Sort-of: `stream_ref` only forces the computation of
the first `n` elements, and leaves the rest of
the stream untouched.

label: stream_remove
title: stream_remove(v, xs) → {stream}
description:
#### stream\_remove(v, xs) → {stream}

Returns a stream that results from
`xs` by removing the first item from `xs` that
is identical (`===`) to `v`.
Returns the original
stream if there is no occurrence.
Lazy? Yes: the result stream forces the construction of each next element

label: stream_remove_all
title: stream_remove_all(v, xs) → {stream}
description:
#### stream\_remove\_all(v, xs) → {stream}

Returns a stream that results from
`xs` by removing all items from `xs` that
are identical (`===`) to `v`.
Returns the original
stream if there is no occurrence.
Recursive process.
Lazy? Yes: the result stream forces the construction of each next
element

label: stream_reverse
title: stream_reverse(xs) → {stream}
description:
#### stream\_reverse(xs) → {stream}

Returns stream `xs` in reverse
order. Iterative process.
The process is iterative, but consumes space `Omega(n)`
because of the result stream.
Lazy? No: `stream_reverse`
forces the exploration of the entire stream

label: stream_tail
title: stream_tail(xs) → {Stream}
description:
#### stream\_tail(xs) → {Stream}

assumes that the tail (second component) of the
pair {x} is a nullary function, and returns the result of
applying that function. Throws an exception if the argument
is not a pair, or if the tail is not a function.
Laziness: Yes: {stream\_tail} only forces the direct tail
stream, but not the rest of the stream, i.e. not the tail
of the tail, etc.

label: stream_to_list
title: stream_to_list(xs) → {list}
description:
#### stream\_to\_list(xs) → {list}

Given stream `xs`, returns a list of same length with
the same elements as `xs` in the same order.
Laziness: No: `stream_to_list` needs to force the whole
stream.

label: stringify
title: stringify(v) → {string}
description:
#### stringify(v) → {string}

returns a string that represents the value `v`, using a
notation that is is consistent with
[JSON](http://www.ecma-international.org/publications/files/ECMA-ST/ECMA-404.pdf),
but also displays `undefined`, `NaN`, `Infinity`, and function objects.
See also [textbook example](https://sourceacademy.org/sicpjs/3.3.5).

label: tail
title: tail(p) → {value}
description:
#### tail(p) → {value}

\*\*primitive\*\*; returns tail (second component of given pair `p`; time: `Theta(1)Theta(1)`.

label: tokenize
title: tokenize(x) → {list}
description:
#### tokenize(x) → {list}

returns the list of tokens that results from lexing the string `str`
